Black swans aside, I’m having a very hard time seeing any “ > $90/bbl by year end” scenarios play out now. Production—particularly from OPEC but also increasingly US unconventional oil—will very likely keep increasing for the rest of the year at these prices. Further, if Biden turns on the spigot from the strategic reserve, that could cause real downward motion in prices (to the point where we could briefly be in bin #4 territory right when it counts). Demand also seems quite unlikely to drive prices up by growing quickly, given “mixed” global outlooks (I’m not exactly seeing headlines about booms in China, Europe, US) and there (frustratingly!) remains a continued threat of another big economic slowdown somewhere globally from a current or future holiday COVID spike, particularly in Europe.

Update reflects today’s surprising and sizable price drop, consistent with the emerging storyline that WTI may actually be on a declining trend now for the near term. Apparently, decreased speculative buying of oil after the US Federal Reserve confirmed that it will begin to taper asset purchases this month may be a key driver. Also out there in the press is a suggestion that the price drop could be partially caused by an increased supply outlook caused by a report that Iran nuclear talks may resume soon, but I’m not buying at all that such protracted and uncertain negotiations would cause such an immediate drop in prices.

First update to my initial forecast, based on an experimental methodology: I've calculated a diverse "envelope" of different visually credible fits to the YTD daily WTI price data, and extrapolated the various models' predictions (and associated error models, based on residuals to YTD data) to the target date. Extrapolation from some higher-order fits seems to create predictions that are more consistent with the most recent (last few weeks/last few months) trends, while simple "straight-line" fits provide a longer-range perspective through time. Since 2021 has had its share of major news events and uncertainty, residual errors from the fits might be interpretable as indicative of the most likely range of deviations--and their relative probability--that might be induced by future news events in the next few months (assuming the events are not too extreme in impact). I'm planning to evaluate this general approach in a number of future forecasts involving time-series data, to see if an ensemble of my "gut-based fits" can systematically outperform my usual "gut-based" forecasting based on simple visual extrapolation or reference to a small number of simple data fitting calculations.

I estimated the chances of extreme outcomes (less than $60/bbl, greater than $90/bbl) loosely, based on the long-term historical WTI price history. Outcomes between $60/bbl and $90/bbl are by far the most likely right now based on current trends (choose your favorite straight-line or curved fit). Large week-to-week fluctuations outside of longer-term trends--unpredictable supply or demand shocks caused by world events--will likely generate large deviations from the long-term trend anyway. More subtle differentiation of probabilities within the $60/bbl to $90/bbl range therefore seems very subjective to me this far in advance!

@Jprice94 @mkarbowsky @Pablo_Vargas This question layers in thoughts about the economy, the state of COVID, inflation and the behavior of OPEC and Russia. Right now I think the safest bet is in the middle. The 60-75 range represents fairly strong demand from strong economic activity. I don't think COVID is going to be a limiting factor on demand because even if there are mask mandates, the economy is up and running. I think the oil producers are biased toward pumping more and holding on to market share. I don't think inflation is going to push oil prices up -- the relationship tends to work the other way. What to you all think?
